    "summary": "Meskalamdug was a ruler of Ur during the Early Dynastic period, dated to approximately 2600–2500 BC. His identity is known primarily from objects discovered in the [[event:1727|Royal Cemetery of Ur]] by archaeologist Leonard Woolley during excavations in the 1920s. A gold helmet, golden bowls, and other luxury grave goods were found bearing his name, indicating he was a person of considerable status, though scholarly debate persists over whether he held the title of king or was a high-ranking military or religious official.\n\nThe richness of the funerary goods associated with Meskalamdug illustrates the extraordinary wealth of Ur's elite during the Early Dynastic III period. His artifacts, now distributed between the British Museum, the University of Pennsylvania Museum, and the Iraqi Museum, rank among the finest examples of ancient Sumerian metalworking. Whether Meskalamdug ruled independently or as a subordinate within a larger political structure remains uncertain, but the material culture connected to him provides important evidence for the political organization and social hierarchy of early Mesopotamian city-states.",
